      <item>
        <title>Checking GPG fingerprints may fool users. Solution included.</title>
        <dc:creator><![CDATA[HulaHoop]]></dc:creator>
        <description><![CDATA[
            <p>A discussion between a Tahoe-LAFS dev and someone shows that showing fingerprints may have loophole that deceives verifiers. A small GPL’d script was written to protect against this. Are we vulnerable to what is described? If so we can add the code and probably fix the wiki instructions.</p>
<aside class="onebox twitterstatus">
  <header class="source">
      <a href="https://twitter.com/least_nathan/status/1078893494779883521" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">twitter.com</a>
  </header>
  <article class="onebox-body">
    <img src="https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/378800000596355184/2b2e573cbfe2ec9bab676568741db67f_400x400.png" class="thumbnail onebox-avatar" width="60" height="60">
<h4>
  <a href="https://twitter.com/least_nathan/status/1078893494779883521" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">
    Nathan Wilcox (least_nathan)
  </a>
</h4>

<div class="tweet">
<a href="https://twitter.com/alfiedotwtf" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">@alfiedotwtf</a> Yes: `gpg --with-fingerprint my-file.asc`. The potential vuln is that if you just grep for the expected fingerprint, an attacker could insert that sequence as their real name or email address. You need to parse that output very explicitly. Wish gpg would print *only* the fp.</div>

